results.notes:
Fruiting in Douglas fir needle litter, moss and grass on the edge of lawn/garden. Beneath mature Rosemary bush.
Cap: dark brown, subviscid nearly black.
Stem: very thick(in relation to cap), bluish slate gray. Heavily pruinose(note thumb print in upper stem of younger posed specimen where handled).
Stem base with whitish bloom. Stems exuding large amount of water when pinched.
Odor: none.
Harvested 4 specimens.

Spore printed a single portion of mature cap directly on slide(slide#1).
Slide#2: removed a single gill and mounted in 3% KOH on second slide.

Slide#2(gill mount):
Basidia: 4 sterigmate. Clavate with slightly swollen apices.
Cheilocystidia: broadly clavate with long extending slender bases, abundant along gill edge. Large globose apices with finger like projections/ornamentation.
Ejected/immature Spores: very small, globose to subglobose, smooth.

Slide#1:
Spore Print: White.
Mounted spore printed slide in 3% KOH.
Spores: broadly ellipsoid to subglobose, slightly pip shaped, thin walled, smooth, medium/small in size.
Thoroughly dehydrated all specimens and bagged for herbarium collection/genetic record.

results.notes:
Two or three similar-looking species of Mycena are commonly found during winter thaws or early spring at this location. Traditionally, M. overholtsii is thought to produce large fruit bodies on coniferous wood during cold/cool weather, often while snow is melting, restricted to high-elevation location in western North America. Recent sequencing efforts suggest this species is also found east of the Rockies, during cold/cool weather, not necessarily at high elevation. Relevant observations (eg. https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/37566563) suggest the eastern NA version produces smaller fruit bodies. Several features associated with this observation appear to support M. overholtsii as the correct ID.
Found during late winter.

Amyloid spores ellipsoid without prominent apiculi, 6-7.5 × 3-4.
Cheilocystidia fusiform (projecting from gill edge with long tapering Necks; cylindric; subcylindric (with slightly variable width).

results.notes:
In a stand of mature spruce.
Deeply rooting stipes apparently attached to decayed cones, although I did not recover such remains.
Caps lacking marginal striations.
Spores 4-6 × 2.5-3.5, pip-shaped.
Pleurocystidia abundant, scattered across the gill surface, some with apical encrustation, some with apex coated (by resin?), others appearing to lack ornamentation. Variously shaped. Some may be cheilocystidia.
The distinction between S. esculenta and S. albipilatus is said to be partly determined by the ornamentation on the pleurocystidia. In the case of this observation, the pleurocystidia seemed to exhibit variable ornamentation, although some were seen to be encrusted with crystals (which reportedly supports S. esculentus). Growth in spruce-dominated habitat supports S. esculentus. However, as I read various reports found online, it appears there may be some questions regarding the taxonomy of this group.
Preserved.

results.notes: I found these in a planter that had been out for the winter. The mini rose plant did not survive the winter. I remember seeing one mushroom last year in this planter, but the mini rose was still alive, so I just plucked it without even looking at what it was. The substrate is potting soil and whatever the mini rose was packed in. There are a lot of wood chips in the soil, as you can see in the photos. I initially used AI to identify it as wavy caps. I took this finding to Facebook, Reddit and iNaturalist, which was a fun ride. Friendly people instructed me on taking better pictures to assist with ID, and the consensus from the local experts was that they were Psilocybe ovoideocystidiata. I hope to have an excellent spore print photo up soon. I have been obsessed with this for the last three days, but I will end this story here. Thanks! For those saying this is Stuntzii the local expert said “The annulus is not pronounced enough to be stuntzii, It’s completely non-existent on most of them.”

results.notes:
A NJMA collection made by an unknown foray participant.
I took this gigantic (dimension recorded but lost) immature fruiting body home and tried to grow it by wrapping the base in a wet paper towel. I succeeded in expanding the cap enough to break away the partial veil to expose the gills, as the pictures show, but the process ceased after a couple of days and the amanita began to wither and rot. I did not save this collection.
In my extensive experience of collecting fungi in the NJ Pine Barrens, Amanita submaculata is quite rate in the outer coastal plain. I can recall only one collection, obs 261109, found some years ago in early November (!), its identity having been confirmed by DNA sequencing. This species is often found in mixed upland deciduous woods and is somewhat variable in appearance, but typically is not very difficult to ID in the field with moderate confidence. Often it has a pleasant fruity odor that could be a bit challenging to detect. To my nose it smells more like a minty toothpaste. The same/similar odor is also characteristic of other taxa in sect. Validae, e.g. A. morrisii and A. umbilicata nom. prov. However, the mushroom in this observation didn’t have it.

results.notes:
Fruiting in soil/duff/needle litter/debris beneath Western red cedar and Douglas fir.
Unusually large/meaty fruiting bodies.
Stems/lower portion dark coco brown contrasting the all black caps.
Harvested 4 specimens.
Analayzed exterior with my Apexel macro lens attachment. NO SETAE=Geoglossum. Also not viscid.
Removed a portion of exterior tissue from multiple fertile cap points and crush mounted in Lugol’s solution and drop of 3% KOH.
MICROSCOPY:
Spores: 7 septate(with 8 sections). All analyzed are 7 septate and slightly curved.
Asci: 8 spored.
Paraphyses: long, thicker than any Geoglossaceae I’ve analyzed. Swollen/curved/curled tips. Extending longer than Asci.
All features match for Geoglossum umbratile.
Dehydrated specimens for herbarium collection/genetic record.
